{"title_page": "Blas de Hinojos", "text_new": "'''Blas de Hinojos''' was a military commander of [[New Mexico]] who was killed by a force of [[Navajo people|Navajo]] warriors led by [[Narbona]] in 1835.\n\nCapitan Blas de Hinojos married Maria de Jesus Trujillo.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\nHis men were poorly paid. In 1834 he received a complaint from the detachment at San Miguel del Bado that they were not able to support themselves or their families.{{sfn|Arellano|Vigil|1985|p=9}}\nIn 1834 he decided to commit his troops to supporting the centralist [[Plan of Cuernavaca]], \nand received an effusive letter from [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Laureano de Zubir\u00eda]], Bishop of Durango,\npraising his decision.{{sfn|Res\u00e9ndez|2005|p=193}}\n\nHinojos led a slaving expedition into Navajo country between 13 October and 17 November 1834, killing sixteen warriors but taking only three captives.\nOn 8 February 1835 Hinojos left [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa F\u00e9]] on a second slaving expedition with a force of almost 1,000 armed men.{{sfn|Locke|2008|p=192}}\nNarbona heard news of the invasion and collected 250 of the best warriors,\nwho made for the {{convert|8000|ft}} high Beesh Lichii'l Bigiizh, or Copper Pass, in the [[Chuska Mountains]] on the route that the Mexicans were sure to take.\nThe Mexican force, although large, was composed of poorly disciplined and inexperienced men who took no precautions.{{sfn|Sides|2007|p=95}}\nOn 28 February 1835 they straggled into Copper Pass.{{sfn|Locke|2008|p=192}}\n\nNarbona held back his forces, who hiding on both sides of the pass.  He told them that when the time was right and not before they would cut the long file of men into small pieces, like cutting a long tree trunk into firewood.\nWhen the signal was given, the Navajos poured arrows into the column, those who had guns fired, and some threw stones or rolled rocks into the gorge.  Taken completely by surprise, both men and horses panicked and were routed.{{sfn|Sides|2007|p=95}} \nHinojos and most of his force died.\nThe survivors made their way beck to Santa Fe, returning on 13 March 1835.{{sfn|Locke|2008|p=192}}\nHinojos was succeeded by [[Albino P\u00e9rez]].{{sfn|Gonzales de la Vara|2000|p=27}}\nThe pass was later renamed Washington Pass, after Colonel [[John M. Washington]], who killed Narbona in 1849.  Today it is called [[Narbona Pass]].\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last1=Arellano|first1=Anselmo F.|last2=Vigil|first2=Julian Josue|title=Las Vegas Grandes on the Gallinas, 1835-1985\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gkVxRKWEQbgC|accessdate=2012-08-22\n |year=1985|publisher=Editorial Telera\u00f1a}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/351/35101814.pdf |date=January\u2013April 2000 |language=Spanish |last=Gonzales de la Vara |first=Martin |title=La Rebelion de los Canaderos en Nuevo Mexico, 1837-1838 |publisher=Escuela Nacional de Antropologia e Historia |journal=Cuicuilco |volume=7 |issue=18 |accessdate=2012-08-22 }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Locke|first=Raymond Friday|title=The Book of the Navajo\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z8e2mfFJa-4C&pg=PA192|accessdate=2012-08-22\n |date=2008-01-01|publisher=Holloway House Publishing|isbn=978-0-87687-500-1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=Res\u00e9ndez|first=Andr\u00e9s|title=Changing National Identities at the Frontier: Texas and New Mexico, 1800-1850\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WDDTHUo_yKQC&pg=PA74|accessdate=2012-07-13\n |year=2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-54319-4}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=Sides|first=Hampton|title=Blood and Thunder: The Epic Story of Kit Carson and the Conquest of the American West\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JzwrddRHDIAC&pg=PA95|accessdate=2012-08-22\n |date=2007-10-09|publisher=Random House Digital, Inc.|isbn=978-1-4000-3110-8|page=95}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Salazar|first=J. Richard|title=Blas de Hinojos: Military personality in oblivion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TLELAAAAYAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Center for Land Grant Studies|pages=24}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hinojos, Blas de}}\n[[Category:1835 deaths]]\n[[Category:Colonial New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican soldiers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Mexican military personnel killed in action]]\n", "text_old": "'''Blas de Hinojos''' was a military commander of [[New Mexico]] who was killed by a force of [[Navajo people|Navajo]] warriors led by [[Narbona]] in 1835.\n\nCapitan Blas de Hinojos married Maria de Jesus Trujillo.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\nHis men were poorly paid. In 1834 he received a complaint from the detachment at San Miguel del Bado that they were not able to support themselves or their families.{{sfn|Arellano|Vigil|1985|p=9}}\nIn 1834 he decided to commit his troops to supporting the centralist [[Plan of Cuernavaca]], \nand received an effusive letter from [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Laureano de Zubir\u00eda]], Bishop of Durango,\npraising his decision.{{sfn|Res\u00e9ndez|2005|p=193}}\n\nHinojos led a slaving expedition into Navajo country between 13 October and 17 November 1834, killing sixteen warriors but taking only three captives.\nOn 8 February 1835 Hinojos left [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa F\u00e9]] on a second slaving expedition with a force of almost 1,000 armed men.{{sfn|Locke|2008|p=192}}\nNarbona heard news of the invasion and collected 250 of the best warriors,\nwho made for the {{convert|8000|ft}} high Beesh Lichii'l Bigiizh, or Copper Pass, in the [[Chuska Mountains]] on the route that the Mexicans were sure to take.\nThe Mexican force, although large, was composed of poorly disciplined and inexperienced men who took no precautions.{{sfn|Sides|2007|p=95}}\nOn 28 February 1835 they straggled into Copper Pass.{{sfn|Locke|2008|p=192}}\n\nNarbona held back his forces, who hiding on both sides of the pass.  He told them that when the time was right and not before they would cut the long file of men into small pieces, like cutting a long tree trunk into firewood.\nWhen the signal was given, the Navajos poured arrows into the column, those who had guns fired, and some threw stones or rolled rocks into the gorge.  Taken completely by surprise, both men and horses panicked and were routed.{{sfn|Sides|2007|p=95}} \nHinojos and most of his force died.\nThe survivors made their way beck to Santa Fe, returning on 13 March 1835.{{sfn|Locke|2008|p=192}}\nHinojos was succeeded by [[Albino P\u00e9rez]].{{sfn|Gonzales de la Vara|2000|p=27}}\nThe pass was later renamed Washington Pass, after Colonel [[John M. Washington]], who killed Narbona in 1849.  Today it is called [[Narbona Pass]].\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last1=Arellano|first1=Anselmo F.|last2=Vigil|first2=Julian Josue|title=Las Vegas Grandes on the Gallinas, 1835-1985\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gkVxRKWEQbgC|accessdate=2012-08-22\n |year=1985|publisher=Editorial Telera\u00f1a}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |url=http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/pdf/351/35101814.pdf |date=January\u2013April 2000 |language=Spanish |last=Gonzales de la Vara |first=Martin |title=La Rebelion de los Canaderos en Nuevo Mexico, 1837-1838 |publisher=Escuela Nacional de Antropologia e Historia |journal=Cuicuilco |volume=7 |issue=18 |accessdate=2012-08-22 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Locke|first=Raymond Friday|title=The Book of the Navajo\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z8e2mfFJa-4C&pg=PA192|accessdate=2012-08-22\n |date=2008-01-01|publisher=Holloway House Publishing|isbn=978-0-87687-500-1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=Res\u00e9ndez|first=Andr\u00e9s|title=Changing National Identities at the Frontier: Texas and New Mexico, 1800-1850\n |url=https://books.google.com